  "prompt": "Has a game developer set a precedent by allowing others to upload a video to YouTube of a user playing one of his games?",
  "response": "Yes, a notable game developer who has set a precedent by explicitly allowing others to upload videos of gameplay to YouTube is Mojang, the creators of *Minecraft*. In 2011, Mojang publicly stated that players were free to monetize *Minecraft* gameplay videos on platforms like YouTube, provided they followed certain guidelines. This was a significant departure from the more restrictive policies of other game developers at the time, and it helped foster a thriving community of content creators around the game.\n\nThis approach has since influenced other developers and publishers to adopt more open policies regarding user-generated content, recognizing the mutual benefits of allowing players to share and monetize their gameplay videos. For example, many developers now include clear statements in their terms of service or community guidelines about the use of their games in videos, often encouraging it as a way to promote their games and engage with the community.\n\nHowever, the specifics of what is allowed can vary widely between developers and publishers, so it\u2019s always important to check their official policies.",
